youtube_search_results.title: STEVE ROSS sings "CHEEK TO CHEEK" by Irving Berlin
youtube_search_results.description: Steve Ross performs Irving Berlin's "Cheek To Cheek" in "Curtain's Up For A Cure": A Broadway Holiday Concert, written and directed by Walter Willison, on December 9, 2013, a benefit for The Huntington's Disease Society Greater New York Chapter at the NYIT Auditorium in New York City. Mr. Ross is an Internationally acclaimed, award winning singer and pianist. After two years at Ted Hook's Backstage he began a run at the Oak Room of the famed Algonquin Hotel which lasted, on and off, for more that 15 years. He appeared on Broadway in Noel Coward's "Present Laughter" which starred Frank Langella. His Off=Broadway tribute to Fred Astaire, "I Won't Dance" ran for five months at the York Theatre and was seen in London and on the high seas.  Mr. Ross has recorded numerous Best Selling CDs, including his tributes to Cole Porter, Noel Coward and Fred Astaire, and his latest, "Good Thing Going", featuring songs by Stephen Sondheim. which will be released in the Spring of 2014. For more about Steve go to: http://steveross.net/

youtube_search_results.title: Steve Ross Performs at the Clark Art Institute - "I Love  a Piano"
youtube_search_results.description:
In this special performance at the Clark, Ross plays the piano designed by Sir Lawrence Alma-Tadema for the Marquand Music Room in honor of the special exhibition Orchestrating Elegance: Alma-Tadema and Design

Dubbed the “Crown Prince of New York cabaret,” Steve Ross has played in virtually all of the world’s fabled clubs from New York and London to Sydney and Saŏ Paolo and is widely considered one of the greatest interpreters of Broadway and  American standards. Although he’ll be playing a much younger piano, Ross will evoke all of the glamour of the piano’s storied past. Enjoy sophisticated song stylings as Ross pays musical tribute to some of America’s greatest composers, including works by Cole Porter, Richard Rodgers, Lorenz Hart, Jerome Kern, Oscar Hammerstein, and Stephen Sondheim, among many others. 

In 1884 the American industrialist Henry Gurdon Marquand (1819–1902) commissioned noted British artist Lawrence Alma-Tadema (1836–1912) to design a Greco-Pompeiian music room for his new Madison Avenue mansion. It was an era when designing luxurious rooms in different styles—Renaissance, Moorish, Japanese, French—was popular among the affluent, and this trend was well represented in other mansions being built along the fashionable avenues in New York. Although Alma-Tadema was most famous as a painter of scenes set in antiquity, he was also known for the imaginative interiors of his own residences. The Marquand music room commission resulted in one of the most evocative interiors of late nineteenth-century New York, featuring a suite of elaborately inlaid furniture alongside textiles, paintings, sculptures, and ancient ceramics in a room that showed off Marquand’s collections while serving as a center for social events and musical performances Orchestrating Elegance: Alma-Tadema and Design (June 4 – September 4, 2017) looks at the history of this exceptional moment in Alma-Tadema’s career and reunites many of the extraordinary components of this lost room for the first time in more than a century.
youtube_search_results.channel_description: The Clark is one of only a handful of institutions globally with a dual mission as an art museum and a distinguished center for research and higher education, dedicated to advancing and extending the public understanding of art.

youtube_search_results.title: STEVE ROSS & KAREN OBERLIN in CHEEK TO CHEEK: Sneek Peek
youtube_search_results.description:
Steve Ross & Karen Oberlin in CHEEK TO CHEEK: The Songs of Fred Astaire & Ginger Rogers, a SNEEK PEEK of their acclaimed show as performed at 54 Below in New York and Le Crazy Coqs in the West End, with Jesse Bielenberg on bass, Directed by Walter Willison. Featuring music & lyrics by Harold Arlen, Irving Berlin, Con Conrad, Howard Dietz, Bernard Dougal, Al Dubin, Edward Eliscu, Dorothy Fields, George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin, Otto Harbach, Gus Kahn, Bert Kalmar, Jerome Kern, Oscar Levant, Johnny Mercer, Herb Magidson, Cole Porter, Harry Ruby, Arthur Schwartz, Harry B. Smith, Harry Warren, Vincent Youmans, from films and shows including “Carefree, “Flying Down to Rio”, “Follow the Fleet”, “Girl Crazy”, “Roberta”, “Shall We Dance”, “Swing Time”, “The Barkleys of Broadway”, “The Gay Divorcee”, “The Story of Vernon and Irene Castle”, “Top Hat”. The show, which tells the story of the Legendary Fred Astaire and Ginger Rogers through their songs, premiered at 54 Below in the summer of 2014, played to capacity crowds and critical acclaim in its UK debut at The Crazy Coqs in the West End in November 2014, and continues to play engagements around the US and abroad.  To learn more about CHEEK TO CHEEK, Steve Ross & Karen Oberlin go to steveross.net and karenoberlin.com. For booking information contact cheektocheekproductions@gmail.com
Videotaped by Alex Pearlman at 54 Below, New York City, in June and July, 2014.

biography: Steve Ross is a renowned American cabaret singer and pianist, known as the "Crown Prince of Cabaret." He specializes in interpreting the Great American Songbook, particularly the works of George Gershwin, Cole Porter, Irving Berlin, and Noël Coward. Ross is celebrated for reviving popular compositions from the early-to-mid 20th century, including ragtime, Tin Pan Alley, show tunes, musical theatre, and patter songs. His performances have taken him around the world, from Rio de Janeiro to Sydney, and he has graced prestigious venues such as Carnegie Hall and Lincoln Center. Ross conducts workshops and Master Classes, and contributes to Vocal Ease, a volunteer organization that brings performances to senior centers in New York City. His sophisticated style and dedication to preserving the legacy of American popular music have earned him recognition, including the upcoming 2025 Darrell Henline Award from the American Songbook Association.

biography: FOURA is an Australian-based electronic music producer and DJ known for her diverse and energetic sound. Her music spans various genres including UK Garage, Break Beat, Speed Garage, House, Techno, Drum and Bass, and Jungle, often infused with emotional elements. FOURA has gained recognition for her unique style and has performed across Australia, including at BIGSOUND in 2022. She has collaborated with other artists such as Geelong-based producer Shuga on tracks like "Pesadão," which showcases her ability to blend different styles, incorporating UK Garage with baile funk rhythms. FOURA has also worked with artists like Jalmar, Subten, and GHS on various releases. Her recent work includes the single "Bankroll" released in March 2025, and she continues to be active in the electronic music scene, crafting gritty anthems and high-octane collaborations.

biography: Mariella Price is an award-winning songwriter and vocalist known for her genre-busting artistry and smooth, rich tone. As a versatile performer, she has graced prestigious stages including Carnegie Hall, Radio City Music Hall, and international jazz festivals. Price has also been featured on NPR's Tiny Desk Concert, showcasing her keen sense of rhythm and distinctive vocal style. She leads her own trio, performing a mix of jazz standards, pop covers, and original compositions. In addition to her performance career, Price is an entrepreneur who founded Jazz Baby Music, combining her passion for jazz standards and popular music with multi-sensory play for children. Her captivating performances blend elements of jazz, blues, Latin, and pop, making her a sought-after artist in New York City's vibrant music scene.

The group, which features DiRubbo on alto sax, Caili O'Doherty on piano, Ugonna Okegwo on bass, and Adam Arruda on drums, has established itself as a notable presence in the New York jazz scene. They regularly perform at prestigious venues such as Smalls Jazz Club in New York City, showcasing their dynamic and skilled musicianship. DiRubbo's quartet is recognized for their live performances, which blend traditional jazz elements with contemporary flair. Their appearances at Smalls Jazz Club, including recent shows in April 2025, have been well-received and are often recorded for archival purposes, allowing their music to reach a wider audience beyond the club's intimate setting.

biography: The Dizzy Gillespie All-Stars is a renowned jazz ensemble that carries on the musical legacy of the legendary trumpeter Dizzy Gillespie. The group performs a repertoire of Gillespie's classic compositions, including "A Night In Tunisia," "Anthropology," "BeBop," and "Salt Peanuts," among others. Led by bassist John Lee, who serves as executive director and producer, the band features a rotating lineup of accomplished musicians, often including former collaborators of Gillespie and rising stars in the jazz world. Notable past members have included Cyrus Chestnut, Lewis Nash, Antonio Hart, and Roy Hargrove. The Dizzy Gillespie All-Stars continue to tour internationally, delighting audiences with the enduring power and freshness of Gillespie's music while maintaining the innovative spirit that characterized his approach to jazz.

WHAT IS FRONT ROW?
Jazz Institute of Chicago presents Front Row, a series of concerts, masterclasses, panel discussions, and talks all about jazz, recorded in our offices on the fifth floor of the Fine Arts Building. Overlooking Michigan Ave, Buckingham Fountain, and Lake Michigan, the performance space is a captivating and distinct venues in Chicago. Jazz Institute of Chicago members receive exclusive first access invitations to Front Row events and performances that are recorded and released on our website at https://www.jazzinchicago.org/frontrow

Since 1969, JIC has produced some of the highest quality jazz experiences in the world and educated the public and students on the power of jazz to connect people and change lives. Front Row is a natural evolution of the Jazz Institute of Chicago’s programs, mission, staff, that takes full advantage of the unique location of our offices in Chicago's Fine Arts Building. 

With exclusive, intimate, performances, discussions, talks, and masterclasses, Front Row documents captivating showcases of the rich tapestry of jazz and furthers the Jazz Institute of Chicago’s mission to promote and nurture jazz in all its amazing forms.

The Jazz Institute of Chicago’s (JIC) mission is to promote and nurture jazz in all its forms. JIC helps jazz music thrive and expand by celebrating the work of past musicians, shining a light on present musicians, and making a brighter way for future musicians. This is realized through community and education programs, 90% of which are free. 

Jazz Institute of Chicago’s pillars include • provide jazz education • preserve the legacy of jazz • develop and support Chicago musicians • build Chicago’s jazz community • foster a thriving Chicago jazz scene

biography: Isaiah Collier is a prodigious jazz saxophonist and composer who has made significant waves in the music world despite his young age. Known for his virtuosic playing and innovative approach to jazz, Collier began his musical journey at age 11 and quickly gained attention for his intuitive proficiency. He has released several acclaimed albums, including "Parallel Universe" (2023), "The World is on Fire" (2024), and "The Almighty" (2024). Collier's music is described as open-ended and designed to connect with another realm, often blending past and future influences in what he calls a "sonic time machine." His groundbreaking work includes the 13-movement suite "The Story of 400 Years," which explores Black American history through music, dance, and storytelling. Collier has garnered significant recognition in the jazz world, being featured on NPR's "Jazz Night In America" and gracing the cover of Downbeat Magazine in 2025. His performances, both with his group The Chosen Few and in other collaborations, continue to push the boundaries of contemporary jazz.

biography: Greg Murphy is a renowned jazz pianist and bandleader who has been a significant figure in the New York City jazz scene since the 1980s. Originally from Chicago, Murphy began his musical journey in 1971 and has since become known for his energetic and soulful performances. He is particularly recognized for his twenty-two-year association with John Coltrane's drummer, Rashied Ali. Murphy leads his own trio, performing at prestigious venues such as Smalls Jazz Club in New York and Arthur's Blues'n'Jazz Club in Dublin. Throughout his career, he has toured internationally, showcasing his talents alongside his trio and other notable musicians. Murphy's contributions to jazz extend beyond his performances, as he has been a major influence in shaping the contemporary New York jazz landscape for decades.

biography: Edwin Vazquez is a versatile musician known for his unique blend of musical styles, including rumba, flamenco, jazz, bolero, R&B, and bossa nova. As a vocal trumpeter, percussionist, and guitarist, Vazquez creates a rich and dynamic sound that he describes as "Gypsy Soul." His performances are characterized by a silky voice, colorful dynamics, and a diverse repertoire of original and popular songs. Vazquez has collaborated with prominent artists, notably contributing to Paul Simon's "Songs of the Cape Man" CD alongside Marc Anthony, Ruben Blades, and Ednita Nazario. He regularly performs at venues such as The Flatiron Room in New York City, where he showcases his ability to fuse various rhythms and styles into a captivating musical experience. Vazquez's artistry extends beyond music, as he is also recognized as a model, further highlighting his multifaceted career in the entertainment industry.

youtube_search_results.title: Kate McGarry - Keith Ganz - Gary Versace – The Subject Tonight Is Love
youtube_search_results.description:
The Subject Tonight Is Love - Coming soon!

The Subject Tonight Is Love is the debut album of critically acclaimed musicians and long time friends Kate McGarry, Keith Ganz and Gary Versace.

On their first crowd funded project the trio reimagines beloved standards, sets music to the words of 14th century Sufi poet Hafiz, and dives into McGarry's catalog of heartfelt originals. The result is a fresh, cinematic approach to jazz that invites the listener to view the heart through many sides of life's prism: spiritual, filial, romantic, maternal, fractured, unconditional - LOVE.

The formidable talents of these Grammy™ nominated musicians are in full bloom on this ambitious outing. Ganz works with various guitar's as well as on bass (and occasionally drums!) while Versace moves fluidly between piano, electric keyboard, organ and accordion. Together they create a richly nuanced sonic canvas. McGarry's voice rings true throughout, painting pictures that penetrate and illumine the human journey.

The trio is currently touring The Subject Tonight Is Love, the trio will be touring and performing the music from this album
"Austere and elegant - An exceptionally appealing blend of folk and jazz." 
~Wall St Journal

" Astute and sensitive"  
~The New York Times

Please contact Marie Le Claire for booking and all other inquires
marieleclairemgmt@gmail.com

biography: Gary Versace is a highly versatile and accomplished jazz musician, proficient as an organist, pianist, and accordionist. He has established himself as one of the most in-demand performers in the New York City jazz scene since 2002. Versace has collaborated with renowned artists such as John Scofield, John Abercrombie, Maria Schneider, Matt Wilson, and Lee Konitz. His musical style spans multiple genres, showcasing charm, beauty, elegance, and technical prowess. Versace's academic background includes a master's degree in music performance from the Eastman School of Music, where he currently serves as an Associate Professor of Jazz Studies. He maintains an active international performing career while balancing his teaching responsibilities, having previously held a tenured position at the University of Oregon's jazz studies program.

Litchfield Jazz Festival: 
The Litchfield Jazz Festival continues a time-honored tradition of showcasing jazz legends and fostering up-and-coming talent that has been in place since our first festival in 1996. "Nothing beats the Litchfield Jazz Festival...an ongoing tradition for those in the know." -- JazzImprov.

Litchfield Jazz Camp:
Founded in 1997, Litchfield Jazz Camp now serves 130-180 residential and day students each week for 1 to 4-week sessions on the campus of Gunnery School in Washington, Connecticut. Run by Litchfield Performing Arts, Inc., a charitable organization dedicated to changing lives through music, the Camp's philosophy is simple: we start with a faculty of amazing and inspiring jazz musicians and to that, we add in eager music students to a non-competitive program. That is how the collaborative, supportive and fun atmosphere at Litchfield Jazz Camp is created. Find out for yourself!
http://litchfieldjazzcamp.com

biography: Spin Cycle is a versatile band known for their eclectic musical repertoire, blending classic rock, funk, soul, dance music, new wave, and power pop from the 1960s to the present day. The group features both male and female lead vocalists, backed by a lineup of experienced and talented musicians. Originating from Birmingham, UK, Spin Cycle made their debut in the music scene with the release of their single "Talog" on May 1, 2025. The band has gained a following for their dynamic live performances, covering a wide range of popular songs and entertaining audiences with their energetic shows. In addition to their full band lineup, Spin Cycle also performs as an acoustic duo under the name "Line Dry," showcasing their musical versatility.

biography: Anaïs Reno is a New York City-based jazz singer and composer who has been making waves in the jazz scene from a young age. She has performed at prestigious venues such as Birdland, Carnegie Hall, The Django, Dizzy's Club, Chris' Jazz Café, Madison Square Garden, and international festivals like the Caramoor Jazz Festival and Edinburgh Jazz Festival. Reno's debut album, "Lovesome Thing: Anaïs Reno Sings Ellington & Strayhorn with the Emmet Cohen Trio," released in 2021, received international critical acclaim and reached number 6 on the jazz charts. She has won several accolades, including awards in the American Traditions Competition, the Mabel Mercer competition, and the Julie Wilson award. Known for her warmly assured style that belies her youth, Reno has been steadily gaining recognition in the jazz world, collaborating with notable musicians and continuing to perform and record, showcasing her talent for interpreting classic jazz repertoire with a fresh perspective.

youtube_search_results.title: Midnight, The Stars And You - Richard Herfeld with Vince Giordano And The Nighthawks
youtube_search_results.description:
"Midnight, The Stars And You" is a popular song written in 1934 by Harry Woods, Campbell and Connelly. Today it is likely best remembered in the version of Ray Noble and his orchestra, with singer Al Bowlly. This version was famously featured in the infamous ballroom scene of the film "The Shining", starring Jack Nicholson.
Here, Vince Giordano and the Nighthawks give it a play at the end of the night at one of their appearances at Iguana in New York City. Vocalist Richard Herfeld joined the band spontaneously to sing the vocal chorus.

biography: Vince Giordano and the Nighthawks are a renowned ensemble specializing in the hot jazz of the 1920s and 1930s. Led by multi-instrumentalist Vince Giordano, this Grammy-winning 11-piece orchestra has been at the forefront of preserving and performing Jazz Age repertoire for nearly five decades. The group is known for their commitment to authenticity and their ability to bring the Roaring Twenties sound to life. They have gained recognition through various performances, including a popular residency at Birdland Jazz Club in New York City in 2025. Giordano's passion and extensive knowledge of the era's music have made the Nighthawks the premier purveyors of this genre, continuing to spread the joy and pathos of a pivotal time in American musical history through their live shows and special events.

biography: Max Light is a highly inventive and talented guitarist known for his jazz performances and compositions. He placed 2nd in the Herbie Hancock International Guitar Competition in 2020, competing against hundreds of other musicians. Light holds a Master's Degree from the Aaron Copland School of Music at Queens College and has been an artist in residence at Hotel 7132 in Vals, Switzerland through Newvelle Records. His musical career includes teaching, with a stint as an instructor at the Washington DC Jazz Academy of Music from 2013-2016, and he continues to offer private lessons in New York City and virtually. Light's discography features collaborations with various artists and his own releases, including the album "Chaotic Neutral" in 2024, which showcases his guitar work alongside other accomplished musicians. He regularly performs and records, contributing to projects such as Christian Sands' "Christmas Stories" and Daryl Gott's "Aperture," both released in 2023.

biography: Jam Session is not a specific band or artist, but rather a term used to describe informal gatherings where musicians play together, often improvising. These sessions are popular in various music genres, particularly jazz. In the context of events and venues, jam sessions provide opportunities for musicians to collaborate and showcase their skills. For example, the Forum Acusticum-Euronoise 2025 Congress is hosting a Jam Session at Sala Trinchera, where acousticians can perform freely with musical instruments. Similarly, venues like The World Stage in South L.A. and Z Club in Joshua Tree regularly host vocal and jazz jam sessions, respectively. These events often feature local host bands or established musicians leading the sessions, creating a dynamic and interactive musical experience for both performers and audiences.

When Google transferred the contents of my YT to an unasked for twin G+ account, leaving my YT empty, I cried, filled the Oceans with my tears, pulled my hair off my head, complained constantly against this intrusion and ranted for hours on end about this abuse, I put my case to the gods and their messengers, and prayed for the eternal damnation of those responsible for all this mess. 

Then, sleeping on it, these gods and their messengers suggested I use this emptied channel to unveil those Playlists that have been scattered around and for quite long kept on private mode in all my other channels, to some practical use. 
They also suggested my elephant icon should be turned face to the right and a "Bis" added to the original channel name.

MoLahBeL3Bis is therefore dedicated to some Jazz'n Blues greats. Jazz'n Blues Playlists, from my 4 older channels are transferred gradually, as time allows.

biography: Pete Matthiessen is a versatile musician and guitarist based in Brooklyn, New York. A graduate of Berklee College of Music, Matthiessen has established himself as a prominent figure in the New York City music scene, particularly in jazz and traditional genres. After initially pursuing independent rock and folk projects, he became deeply involved in the city's gypsy jazz community. Matthiessen's musical journey began at age 12, and his passion was further ignited by experiences at the National Guitar Workshop in his hometown of New Milford, Connecticut. He is known for his performances at venues like St. Mazie Bar and Supper Club in Brooklyn, where he regularly plays jazz sets during happy hour shows. Matthiessen's expertise extends beyond performing, as he also shares his knowledge as an instructor at the New York City Guitar School.

youtube_search_results.description:
Lyrics and Music is a show of original songs that explores the secrets of one man’s soul through song and one man’s life through music.

A native of the historical neighborhood of Harlem in New York City, Darnell White is a graduate LaGuardia High School of Music and Art and The Juilliard School. A noted staple in New York City’s music scene, Darnell has developed a pristine reputation as a performer, composer, and musical director. As an MD he has collaborated with a number of noted artists including Melba Moore, Brian McKnight, Blaine Krauss, Amma Ossei, Willis White, Angela Birchett, David LaMarr, Carlton Jumel Smith, and many more!

Both as a performer and resident artist, Darnell’s graced the stages of New York’s major venues including 54 Below, The Iridium, Birdland, Carnegie Hall, Lincoln Center, Smokey Joe’s Cafe, and Sid Gold’s to name a few. Darnell recently served as Musical Director for the off-Broadway show Revelation The Musical as well as the film adaptation of Gospel at Colonus. He is currently the MD for a few churches in the New York area and the chorusmaster for Trilogy: An Opera Company in Newark, NJ. Both as a vocalist & instrumentalist, Darnell is well versed in many genres as he believes music should always be approached first from a place of pure expression. It is indeed the desire to share his expressions through the gift of music that have left no style or genre outside his reach. Darnell is highly recognized as one of New York City’s top vocal coaches and is always accepting new talent into his studio.

Myrna Bain (November 27, 1939 – April 12, 2007) born Myrna Delores Bain, was an activist, grass-roots organizer, scholar and writer. She was an influential member of several organizations founded by LGBTI women of color, most notably: The Kitchen Table: Women of Color Press (with Audre Lorde, Cherrie Moraga and Hattie Gusset). Bain was also a renowned professor of Black Studies for the City University of New York for several decades (at Hunter College, John Jay College and New York Institute of Technology). The Myrna Bain Scholarship at John Jay College is dedicated to her memory. en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myrna_Bain

biography: Darnell White is a prominent figure in New York City's music scene, known for his exceptional skills as a pianist, composer, and musical director. A native of Harlem, White has established himself as a versatile artist, equally at home in jazz and Broadway settings. His talents have been recognized with the 2025 Manhattan Association of Cabarets Downtown Piano Instrumentalist Award. White frequently performs with his trio at renowned venues like Roxy Bar and The Django Jazz Club in NYC, delivering lively and spirited jazz performances. His musical accomplishments extend beyond live performances, as he has served as a music director for Broadway singers and participated in tribute concerts honoring legendary artists such as Nina Simone and Aretha Franklin. White's contributions to the music industry also include involvement in film adaptations of musicals and collaborations with other Broadway stars, showcasing his broad range of musical expertise and his significant impact on the contemporary jazz and theater scenes.

biography: Michael Eckroth is an accomplished pianist and keyboardist based in New York City. He has established himself as a versatile musician, equally adept in jazz and Latin American music forms. Eckroth has performed extensively with renowned jazz artists such as John Scofield, Ron McClure, Eliot Zigmund, and Paul McCandless. His career spans over 15 years in New York, during which he has played at major jazz clubs and various local stages. Eckroth leads his own trio, exploring diverse musical styles and collaborating with guest artists. His recent projects include interpreting Wayne Shorter's compositions through Cuban and Puerto Rican rhythms, showcasing his innovative approach to jazz and Latin fusion. As an active performer, Eckroth continues to contribute to the vibrant New York jazz scene and performs at venues worldwide.

His musical repertoire extends beyond jazz, encompassing rock and other genres. Jones is actively involved in creating new music, with his latest single "Greatest is Love" showcasing his ability to craft hopeful and meaningful compositions. He is set to release a new EP in June 2025 and has an upcoming album titled "Medicine the Man" scheduled for worldwide release in January 2025. His involvement in events like the Free The Music Festival demonstrates his ongoing engagement with the music community.

biography: Brian Charette is a Hammond-endorsed organist and accomplished jazz musician. He consistently ranks near the top of the Downbeat Critic's Poll and has released 18 critically acclaimed albums. Charette leads various ensembles, including the Brian Charette Sextette, which performs modern funky organ chamber music with horns. He is active on the international jazz scene, with performances scheduled at venues like The Django in New York City and the Cotton Club in Tokyo. Beyond his work as a bandleader, Charette contributes to the music community by writing for publications such as Downbeat, Keyboard, and NYC Jazz Record. His musical style blends traditional organ jazz with contemporary elements, showcasing his versatility as both a performer and composer.

biography: Caleb Wheeler Curtis is a versatile jazz musician and composer based in New York, known for his proficiency on alto saxophone, trumpet, and sopranino saxophone. He leads an innovative groove-oriented improvising quartet called "Undercurrents," featuring renowned musicians like Mark Whitfield Jr. on drums, Colson Jimenez on bass, and Rogerio Boccato on percussion. Curtis has garnered attention for his ambitious musical projects, including a double album featuring collaborations with notable artists such as Sean Conly, Michael Sarin, Eric Revis, and Justin Faulkner. His musical style blends traditional jazz elements with contemporary approaches, as evidenced in his album "The True Story of Bears and the Invention of the Battery." Curtis has also been a member of the Captain Black Big Band and the group Ember, showcasing his versatility across various jazz ensembles. His performances, including appearances at venues like LunÀtico in Brooklyn, highlight his growing prominence in the jazz scene.

youtube_search_results.title: Axel Tosca invites you to Made in New York Jazz Festival - Montenegro 2019
youtube_search_results.description:
One of the most dynamic young pianists on the scene is coming to Montenegro!

Axel Tosca brings a hypnotic blend of Jazz, Timba and Funk. Born in Cuba to Cuban singer/folkloric songwriter Albert Tosca, and world renown Cuban vocalist Xiomara Laugart, his musical influences were everywhere, and his fate was sealed. 
Now based in New York, Laugart continues to grow musically. Of his future, he says “my goal is to just keep upgrading my talent and my soul. I love the world.”

Save the dates 🔜 June 14th to 16th!
youtube_search_results.channel_description:
Rabbit Records doo, a Montenegro-based company, was established in February 2011. Our primary focus is on music publishing, but we are also involved in marketing and consulting services, as well as audio/video production. Our extensive range of business activities includes the successful management of the Ethno Jazz Club Sejdefa located in the city center.

Through our music publishing services, we strive to promote less mainstream music genres such as jazz, blues, classical, rock, fusion, and hip-hop music, as well as artists from Montenegro who create original music in these genres. Our aim is to bring attention to talented musicians and their work while also popularizing unique musical styles in the Montenegrin market.

youtube_search_results.title: Axel Tosca: Soulful Afro-Cuban Jazz Master
youtube_search_results.description:
Pete's Voodoo Room presents the story of 3x Grammy-nominated Axel Tosca, a Cuban jazz pianist who blends jazz, classical, Hip-Hop, and Afro-Cuban rhythms. Born into a prestigious musical family in 1983, Cuba, Tosca's early education in music was shaped by his parents, renowned Cuban artists, and mentorship under Miriam Valdez. His journey led him to the U.S. in 2005, where he became a sought-after performer and collaborator. Tosca’s debut album in 2016 featured notable artists like Xiomara Laugart and Jeff "Tain" Watts. Currently based in New York, Tosca continues to push jazz's boundaries, collaborating with legends like George Clinton and Bad Bunny.

biography: Cordeone is an independent artist and multi-instrumentalist known for his unique blend of musical styles, including Blues, Jazz, Funk, Reggae, Fado, and Brazilian music. As a self-described "music mixologist," he composes and performs original works in English, French, and Portuguese, incorporating elements of Hip Hop, Gospel, Soul, Kompa, and Gypsy Jazz. Cordeone leads the band Fado Manouche and has released several albums, including "Latchi Raïsa" and "Uma História Simples," the latter of which won the 2019 Best Fado Album at the International Portuguese Music Awards (IPMAs). His performances often feature traditional Fado poems, including works by Fernando Pessoa and his own compositions, and he has expanded his sound by incorporating the standup bass. Cordeone is also known for his innovative approach to the accordion, fusing musical genres from around the world, and regularly shares videos showcasing his skills on accordion and Portuguese guitar.

biography: Jonathan Michel is a versatile bassist, composer, and arranger known for blending jazz, hip hop, R&B, gospel, and his Haitian heritage into his music. Originally from Connecticut, Michel began his musical journey playing guitar and trombone before settling on the bass at age nine. He has developed a large tone and adaptable style that places him firmly in the modern jazz scene. Michel's musical accomplishments include performances at renowned New York City venues like Smalls and Mezzrow, as well as touring with his own projects. He has released original music available on Bandcamp and is associated with Imani Records. In 2025, Michel is participating in concerts celebrating the 30th anniversary of The Jazz Gallery, an important milestone in the international jazz scene. His ongoing tour, which began in Rochester, is bringing his music to audiences across various cities.

youtube_search_results.title: Miss Maybell and the Jazz Age Artistes
youtube_search_results.description:
Miss Maybell and the Jazz Age Artistes are known for their large repertoire of Prohibition-Era Jazz, Ragtime and Blues. Sourcing their tunes directly from dusty old records and antique sheet music, the group brings new life to songs created over 100 years ago. With this unique sound and dedication they were recently featured on The NPR Show “Person, Place, Thing” With Randy Cohen. Building a sizable following from residencies at Birdland Theater as well as venues such as Flatiron Room, Chez Josephene, The Back Room, St Mazie and Sleep No More, they have also built a respectable international following from performing regularly in Europe, recently headlining Sevilla Swing in Seville, Spain and selling out a week of shows at Marian's Jazz Room in Bern, Switzerland.

Led by vocalist and multi-instrumentalist Miss Maybell, the group is composed of some of NYC's finest musicians, such as Charlie Judkins on Piano, Brian Nalepka (of Broadway's "Crazy for You") on Bass, and Andy Stein (Two time Grammy winner and Violinist on "A Prairie Home Companion") on Violin.

biography: Miss Maybell & The Jazz Age Artistes are a musical group known for their dedication to reviving Prohibition-Era Jazz, Ragtime, and Blues from the 1920s and 1930s. The ensemble sources their repertoire directly from vintage 78 records and antique sheet music, breathing new life into century-old compositions. Their unique sound and commitment to preserving this musical era have earned them recognition, including a feature on NPR's show "Person, Place, Thing" with Randy Cohen. The group comprises some of New York City's finest vintage jazz musicians, including Charlie Judkins on piano and Brian Nalepka on bass. They perform regularly at venues across New York, such as St. Mazie Bar and Supper Club in Brooklyn and Birdland Theater in Manhattan, showcasing their extensive collection of revitalized classic tunes to modern audiences.

biography: Tardo Hammer is a highly respected jazz pianist and bandleader based in New York City. He leads the Tardo Hammer Trio, a modern jazz piano trio that regularly performs at renowned jazz venues like Smalls Jazz Club and Mezzrow in New York. Hammer's musical style is rooted in bebop and hard bop traditions, showcasing his skillful improvisation and deep understanding of jazz harmony. Throughout his career, he has collaborated with numerous notable jazz musicians, including playing in bands led by Bill Hardman and Junior Cook. As a bandleader, Hammer has released several albums and continues to be an active presence in the NYC jazz scene, with frequent performances alongside accomplished sidemen such as bassist Lee Hudson and drummer Keith Balla. His trio's performances are known for their swinging intensity and sophisticated interplay between the musicians.

Music | Travels | Art | Dublin | Hiking | Activism | Train Journey | Drone Aerial

I was born in Tortolì, a small town on the east coast of Sardinia. My grandparents were the stationmaster and the town clerk. When I was a student in my High School my favourite subject was philosophy, but I graduated in Economics and I specialized in International Marketing Management. I'm passionate about the Internet, the communication and new technology and I pay my bills working in the marketing industry. I love make videos, play harmonica, listen jazz, dance swing, act in experimental theatre plays, travel by train and climb mountains. I use to write mushy stories and heterodox economics books. I travel by bike and Vespa. I live in an apartment converted from an old distillery in the centre of Dublin.

Welcome to Soapbox Gallery YouTube Channel. Here you can view concerts filmed live at Soapbox Gallery.

Soapbox Gallery is dedicated to presenting music, performance and works of art that engage the issues of our time. 

The room itself is a beautiful, meditative environment that was designed with state-of-the art acoustics to showcase exceptional musicianship from around the world.

The gallery was founded on the premise that art and culture are powerful reminders of our shared humanity, which can help to shape identity and promote social evolution. 

Soapbox was inspired by the idea that a simple, humble box–that one stands on and delivers a speech from–can start a movement and perhaps even help to change the world.

It’s our mission to create space for civil conversation between those with differing views. The intent of our programming is to create a dialogue where everyone has a seat at the table.

biography: Randy Ingram is an accomplished jazz pianist and composer known for his contemporary harmonic approach and sleek rhythmic sensibility. He leads the Randy Ingram Trio, a group that has garnered critical acclaim for their impressive musicianship and consistent performances. Ingram's work has been praised by notable publications such as The New York Times and WBGO, with his album "The Means of Response" receiving particular recognition for its graceful compositions inspired by current political events. The trio, which has featured bassist John Hébert and drummer Billy Drummond, performs regularly at prestigious jazz venues like Smalls Jazz Club in New York and Birdland Neuburg in Germany. Ingram's style draws comparisons to influential pianist Bill Evans, and his music is characterized by its beauty and hopeful resistance to chaotic times.

biography: Jason Marshall is a talented saxophonist and bandleader known for his work with the Jason Marshall Quartet. His musical style encompasses the joy and depth of Black American Music, showcasing his skills as a composer, arranger, and performer. Marshall has been active in the jazz scene since the early 2000s, leading his own ensemble and collaborating with renowned artists. He has performed with the Roy Hargrove Big Band, RH Factor, Aretha Franklin, The Temptations, and Chaka Khan, among others. The Jason Marshall Quartet regularly performs at prestigious jazz venues, including Smalls Jazz Club in New York City and The Django, where they captivate audiences with their dynamic performances. Marshall's contributions to the jazz world have earned him recognition as a versatile and accomplished musician in the contemporary jazz landscape.

youtube_search_results.title: CHAMPIAN FULTON TRIO
youtube_search_results.description:
2 March 2023 at Al Vapore  - Marghera - Venezia - Italy

Champian Fulton - vocals, piano
Lorenzo Conte - bass guitar
Joris Dudli - drums

Born in Oklahoma, Champian Fulton is considered one of the most gifted pure jazz musicians of her generation. She grew up with music at home; her mother and father (jazz trumpeter and educator Stephen Fulton) recognized her fascination with music at an early age. The presence of her father's musician friends, including Clark Terry and Major Holley, inspired her focus on jazz. Her first paid musical engagement was with his band on Clark Terry's 75th birthday; she was 10 years old. Since then, her piano and vocal skills have been recognized by peers and critics as distinctive and sophisticated. This young woman from Oklahoma captivates audiences in New York's finest jazz halls and concert halls around the world.
A mainstay of New York's vibrant jazz scene, she has performed with musical royalty such as Lou Donaldson, Frank Wess, Scott Hamilton, Buster Williams, and Louis Hayes. From New York to Barcelona, Champian's swinging style and charismatic performances have made her a keeper of the jazz legacy. Champian's heroes include Bud Powell, Red Garland, Erroll Garner, Count Basie, Sarah Vaughan and Dinah Washington.
Champian was named pianist and singer of 2019 by hot house magazine and the jazzmobile readers' poll.

The rhythm section consists of Venetian double bassist Lorenzo Conte, who has been active for many years with many musicians on the New York scene, and Swiss drummer Joris Dudli, who has also always been linked to musicians from overseas.

"Al Vapore" non è solo sinonimo di musica dal vivo: il locale si pone come vetrina e palcoscenico della vita artistica locale, comprendendo in essa anche le arti figurative. biography: Champian Fulton is an acclaimed jazz pianist and vocalist based in New York City. She leads the Champian Fulton Trio, a jazz ensemble that has gained recognition for their performances at renowned venues such as Mezzrow Jazz Club and Smalls Jazz Club in New York. Fulton's musical style is deeply rooted in jazz, having been immersed in the genre since childhood. Her talents have earned her praise from Downbeat magazine and the New York press. The trio, which includes Fukushi Tainaka on drums and Mike Karn on bass, regularly tours internationally, showcasing Fulton's skills as both a pianist and singer. Fulton has collaborated with notable musicians and ensembles, including appearances as a special guest with larger jazz orchestras. Her performances extend beyond the United States, with the trio making appearances in Shanghai and garnering a following in Europe, particularly in France.

youtube_search_results.title: Bennett Paster Trio - presented in partnership with the Santa Fe Music Collective
youtube_search_results.description: Keyboardist, composer and producer, Bennett Paster, grew up in Albuquerque and attended Albuquerque Academy from 6th to 12th grade where he studied with music teacher Ken Adkins, who introduced him to jazz. Upon graduating from The Academy, he attended the New England Conservatory of Music and Tufts University after which he moved to New York City in 1996 where he has built a career as a creative and versatile musician. Paster has performed at clubs, concerts and festivals in the United States, the Caribbean, South and Central America, Central and South Asia and throughout Europe and has been a featured performer with jazz luminaries including Wallace Roney, Keb Mo, Kurt Elling, Peter Erskine, Billy Hart, Albert “Tootie” Heath, and Yosvany Terry. He has also performed with musical theater and cabaret stars Christine Ebersole, Ann Hampton Calloway and Michael Cerveris. Paster last performed in New Mexico in 2013 at the Outpost, and now, ten years later, he returns with his new trio featuring Gary Wang on bass and Tony Mason on drums, and with new compositions. His mission statement for this band and for his forthcoming recording comes from his search for music that is an antidote to the complex world that we find ourselves in, music that soothes and that is, as he puts it, “at the crossroads of Beauty and Groove, music that is, in a word, Radiant.”
youtube_search_results.channel_description: Outpost Performance Space is a non-profit, member-supported, community based performing arts venue that presents over 100 shows a year–jazz, experimental, folk, international, spoken word, youth performances and more. Year-round education programs include Jazz and Latin music classes for youth and adults and visual art is represented at the Inpost Artspace Gallery. Outpost also presents the NM Jazz Festival each July (since 2006).

biography: Anaïs Reno is a New York-based jazz singer and composer who has been actively involved in the performing arts since a young age. She has performed at prominent venues including Birdland, Carnegie Hall, Rose Hall, The Django, Dizzy's Club, and Madison Square Garden, as well as international jazz festivals in Edinburgh and Caramoor. Reno's debut album, "Lovesome Thing: Anaïs Reno Sings Ellington & Strayhorn With The Emmet Cohen Trio," released in 2021, received international acclaim and reached number 6 on the jazz chart. Her upcoming album, "Lady of the Lavender Mist," featuring Peter Bernstein, is set to release on May 23, 2025. To celebrate this release, Reno will be performing at The Django on May 19, 2025, with sets at 7:30 and 9 PM, accompanied by Peter Bernstein, Martin Wind, and Matt Wilson.

biography: Champian Fulton is an acclaimed jazz pianist and vocalist known for her artistry and captivating performances. Leading her own quartet, Fulton has established herself as a prominent figure in the contemporary jazz scene. Her musical style is deeply rooted in jazz traditions, with a particular focus on interpreting jazz standards. Fulton has garnered praise from DownBeat magazine and the New York press for her exceptional talent. She regularly performs at renowned jazz venues, including Smalls and Mezzrow in New York City, and has toured internationally, showcasing her skills at jazz clubs and festivals worldwide. Fulton's discography includes collaborative works, such as the intimate album "At Home" recorded with Swedish saxophonist and clarinetist Klas Lindquist. Her performances are characterized by her "galvanizing presence" and ability to transform each song into a work of art through her skillful piano playing and emotive vocals.

biography: Ken Fowser is a talented saxophonist and jazz musician who has established himself as one of the finest players of his generation. Known for his lyrical approach to line construction and deep harmonic sensibility, Fowser has been active on the New York jazz scene since 2005. He leads his own quintet and has performed with notable musicians such as David Hazeltine, Ugonna Okegwo, and Willie Jones III. Fowser's musical style builds upon the jazz tradition while continuing to develop his own unique voice. He has released several albums, including his latest recording "Morning Light" on the Posi-tone label, which features eleven original compositions. The Ken Fowser/Behn Gillece Quintet, one of his earlier projects, won the prestigious Generations International Jazz Competition in 2010 in San Francisco. Fowser's performances have taken him to venues around the world, and he continues to be an active presence in the jazz community, regularly playing at clubs like Smalls Jazz Club in New York and Chris' Jazz Cafe in Philadelphia.

biography: The Blicker Blues Band, fronted by guitarist Erik Blicker, is known for their blues/rock fusion sound reminiscent of the American blues heyday. Erik Blicker, who also has a successful career as a score composer, leads the band with his guitar and vocals. The group's lineup includes Eric Finland on keys, Eric Kalb on drums, and Josh Lattanzi on bass. They are regular performers at The Flatiron Room in New York City, where they play extended sets from 9:00 PM to midnight. The band's performances blend elements of traditional blues with a modern rock edge, creating a unique fusion that appeals to both blues purists and contemporary music fans. Their live shows, such as those at the Flat Iron Room, showcase their musical prowess and ability to captivate audiences with their energetic performances and skillful musicianship.

youtube_search_results.description:
This video was from a concert featuring the music of Billie Holiday and poetry of Frank O'Hara. The searing pain of Billie Holiday’s death was captured by long time East End resident Frank O’ Hara in his poem The Day Lady Died. O’Hara, a fine pianist himself, was a fixture in the East Village in the 1950s, and a denizen of its clubs. 


This show was part of the EAST ENDERS music series curated by former New York Times music critic Peter Watrous. The 2019 summer series featured a thematic jazz program rooted in the era of Abstract Expressionism, featuring some of the best musicians working in New York.

Kevin Sun is a saxophonist and composer living in New York City. His music has been called “...intense, harmonically virtuosic and compositionally complex" by DownBeat Magazine, and he has released four albums to date—most recently ♡ BIRD in August 2021, which landed on the Boston Globe's "60 best albums of the year."

Sun has also recorded four albums with the ensembles Mute, Earprint, and Great On Paper, and he appears on recordings led by Jacob Garchik, Dana Saul, and Xiongguan Zhang.

In addition to performing in the U.S., Sun has performed extensively in China and has served as the Artistic Director of the Blue Note China Jazz Orchestra. In 2021, Sun was named a Finalist for the Jerome Hill Foundation Artist Fellowship.

biography: Peter Watrous is a renowned guitarist and former New York Times music critic who continues to perform actively in the jazz scene. He leads his own groups, including the Peter Watrous Quintet and Peter Watrous Trio, showcasing his musical talents in various ensemble formats. Watrous has been featured at notable venues such as Smalls in New York City and The Green Room at the Sag Harbor Cinema. His performances often include collaborations with other accomplished musicians, such as bassist Charlie Lincoln and drummer Jon Mele. As a critic-turned-performer, Watrous brings a unique perspective to his music, blending his deep understanding of jazz history with his own creative expression on the guitar. His ongoing performances and archival recordings contribute to the vibrant contemporary jazz landscape.

biography: Marianne Solivan is an accomplished jazz vocalist known for her dynamic performances and collaborations with renowned musicians. Her musical style blends traditional jazz elements with contemporary influences, showcasing her versatility as an artist. Solivan has released multiple albums as a leader, including "Prisoner of Love," "Spark," "RE-ENTRY" in 2024, and her sixth studio effort "Break's Over" in January 2025. The latter features esteemed musicians Buster Williams on bass, Brandon McCune on piano, and Jay Sawyer on drums. Solivan's career has been marked by frequent live performances, including regular gigs during her time at Berklee College of Music and The New England Conservatory. She continues to tour internationally, with upcoming performances scheduled in Syracuse and Brittany, France in 2025. Solivan is also recognized for her songwriting abilities, having composed both music and lyrics for several tracks on her albums.

youtube_search_results.title: Aruán Ortiz & John Hébert & Gerald Cleaver - Klavierhaus Merta, Linz, Austria, 2017-10-08
youtube_search_results.description:
Aruán Ortiz & John Hébert & Gerald Cleaver - Live at Klavierhaus Merta, Linz, Austria, 2017-10-08

Black and Tan Fantasy (Duke Ellington)
Open & Close and The Sphinx (Ornette Coleman) 
Los Tres Golpes (Ignacio Cervantes)

Aruán Ortiz: piano
John Hébert: bass
Gerald Cleaver: drums

Der aus Santiago de Cuba stammende Pianist Aruán Ortiz, der keinen Geringeren als Muhal Richard Abrams als seinen Mentor nennt, beherrscht eine enorme Bandbreite von modernen Jazz-Piano-Dialekten. Diese reichen von Thelonious Monk über Herbie Hancock und Paul Bley bis zu Andrew Hill. Afro-Kubanisches findet sich selbstredend ebenso wie Hard-Bop in Reinkultur. Auch freie Felder steuert er an. Alles mit der nötigen Virtuosität und einem ganz persönlich ausgerichteten Bekenntnis zum Eklektizismus. Und mit Bassist John Hébert und Schlagzeuger Gerald Cleaver formiert Aruan Ortiz ein Trio, das zu den formidabelsten seiner Art in den USA gezählt werden kann.

CD-Tipp: ARUAN ORTIZ TRIO / Hidden Voices / Intakt CD 258/2016

youtube_search_results.description:
"FloodStage" + "Ten Hands" Le 10 décembre 2013 / JOHN HEBERT contrebasse, GERALD CLEAVER batterie, BENOÎT DELBECQ piano http://www.johnhebert.com/html/slideshow.php

Ce trio a été formé à New York par John Hébert en 2009. Il s'est produit alors à New York et a enregistré le disque « Spiritual lover » (Clean Feed) qui a reçu des éloges de la critique de jazz internationale. Hébert et Cleaver incarnent une paire rythmique exceptionnelle, la crème de la crème du jazz New-Yorkais. Au sein de ce trio qui s'apprête à enregistrer son prochain disque, ils croisent leurs routes avec la démarche du pianiste et compositeur Benoît Delbecq, un important musicien de la scène européenne du jazz contemporain, un musicien qui combine l'âme du jazz au piano préparé cher à John Cage.

Avec le soutien du French American Jazz Exchange, un programme FACE et l'Ambassade de France aux Etats-Unis, en collaboration avec la Doris Duke Foundation, Mid Atlantic Arts Fondation, la Florence Gould Foundation, la SACEM et l'Institut Français

The Scott Club Concert Series showcasing the Everett grand piano featured Kalamazoo based pianist Grayson Nye. Grayson is a member of the Last Gasp Collective, Fake Baseball, Saxquatch and the Bridge Band, and recently has joined in a band fronted by The Lasso. biography: Matt Snow is a talented bassist and bandleader known for hosting popular jam sessions at Smalls Jazz Club in New York City. As a versatile musician, Snow has performed with a wide range of artists, from the WDR Big Band in Cologne to jazz luminaries such as Ron Carter, Eric Reed, and Christian McBride. His regular jam sessions at Smalls attract a diverse array of musicians, showcasing his ability to lead and collaborate with various instrumentalists. Snow's performances often feature a rotating cast of skilled players, including saxophonists, pianists, and drummers, highlighting his role as both a performer and a curator of jazz talent. His late-night sessions, which sometimes extend into the early morning hours, have become a staple of the New York jazz scene, providing a platform for both established and up-and-coming artists to showcase their skills in an improvisational setting.

biography: Matt Cappy is a talented trumpet player and bandleader known for his warm trumpet sound and diverse musical style. As the leader of the Matt Cappy Quintet, he blends elements of jazz, soul, Latin, and hip-hop in his compositions. Cappy has released at least two albums, including his sophomore effort "Tales of the Tape," which showcases his creative approach to various genres. He actively performs with his band at notable venues such as Django in New York City and Zinc Bar. Cappy's music career includes touring and live performances, with concert dates extending into 2025 and beyond. His recent work includes a cover of the Genesis song "Follow You Follow Me," demonstrating his versatility and willingness to explore different musical territories.

biography: The Birdland Big Band is a renowned jazz ensemble that performs regularly at the iconic Birdland Jazz Club in New York City. Known for their thrilling and original mix of jazz and funk, the band takes the stage every Friday night, showcasing their dynamic sound and impressive musicianship. The BBB, as they're sometimes called, also headlines two special weeks each year at Birdland, further cementing their status as a staple of the New York jazz scene. Their performances are characterized by high energy and virtuosic playing, featuring a roster of accomplished musicians who bring the drama of big band jazz to life. The Birdland Big Band has become a must-see attraction for jazz enthusiasts, offering a powerful and engaging live music experience in the heart of Manhattan.

youtube_search_results.title: Louis Hayes: Music on Jazz at Linciln center:
youtube_search_results.description: The Lessons from Our Masters series features a master of jazz alongside a multigenerational band. Tonight’s master is drummer Louis Hayes. While still in his teens in 1956, Louis Hayes moved to New York and joined the Horace Silver Quintet, spending the following couple of years working with greats like John Coltrane and Curtis Fuller, and then joining Cannonball Adderley’s quintet in 1959. He has since become one of the most recorded drummers in jazz history, and one of the players to most successfully navigate the changes in jazz since the hard bop era. Though his résumé also includes working with Sonny Rollins, Dizzy Gillespie, Yusef Lateef, Ravi Shankar, J.J. Johnson, Ray Brown, Wes Montgomery, and countless more, he has spent the last several decades as a leader, mobilizing some of the tightest and most cohesive groups in the business. For both the band and the audience, tonight’s performance will be a lesson from a true master.

biography: Louis Hayes is a renowned jazz drummer and NEA Jazz Master who leads the group Louis Hayes and the Jazz Communicators. With a career spanning over 70 years, Hayes has been instrumental in shaping the art of jazz drumming, known for his impeccable sense of feel and propulsive swing. His unmistakable style is characterized by excitement tempered with poise, and he is considered one of the last active drummers from jazz's hard-bop era. Hayes has performed with some of the most soulful artists in jazz history, and continues to be a prominent figure in the contemporary jazz scene. The Jazz Communicators, featuring Hayes on drums alongside accomplished musicians on tenor saxophone, vibraphone, piano, and bass, regularly perform at prestigious venues such as SMOKE Jazz Club in New York City, showcasing Hayes's enduring influence and mastery of jazz drumming.

Globally acclaimed jazz visionary José James unveils his next single, "They Sleep, We Grind (For Badu)", a hypnotic, groove-drenched odyssey inspired by the queen of neo-soul, Erykah Badu. Anchored by a pulsing bassline and a sparse, almost haunting beat, the track is as much a meditation as it is a battle cry and nod to 70s music and kung fu influences. This isn’t just a song; it’s an anthem for the artists and dreamers grinding in the shadows, waiting for their moment to step into the light.

José James - vocals
BIGYUKI - keys, synths
Kyle Miles - bass

James, who founded his own label Rainbow Blonde Records, is recognized for his creative vision and ability to push boundaries in the music industry. His work is often compared to that of musical icons like Miles Davis, Erykah Badu, and David Bowie. Throughout his career, James has consistently demonstrated his versatility as a vocalist, producer, and creative force in the jazz and contemporary music scenes.

youtube_search_results.title: Betty Carter's Jazz Ahead The Kennedy Center Giorgi Mikadze &  Roni Eytan 2013
youtube_search_results.description:
Betty Carter's Jazz Ahead - The Kennedy Center in Washington, D.C. 2013
Giorgi Mikadze -- Piano 

The John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts will present Betty Carter's Jazz Ahead, the international jazz residency, performance and composition project discovering and presenting the next generation of jazz greats, March 11-22, 2013, at the Kennedy Center in Washington, D.C. Under the direction of Jason Moran, Kennedy Center Artistic Advisor for Jazz, the Jazz Ahead program identifies outstanding, emerging jazz artist-composers in their mid-teens to age twenty-five, and brings them together under the tutelage of experienced artist-instructors who coach and counsel them, helping to polish their performance, composing, and arranging skills.

The two-week residency program includes daily workshops and rehearsal with established jazz artists and culminates in three concerts on the Kennedy Center Millennium Stage, which will be broadcast live over the Internet.

Betty Carter, who possessed one of this era's most extraordinary voices, was devoted to jazz education. Her Jazz Ahead program, which she brought to the Kennedy Center in 1998, has helped launch the careers of several of today's stars, including Cyrus Chestnut, Jason Moran, and Jacky Terrasson.

VISTEL BROTHERS
Jorge and Maikel Vistel come from Santiago de Cuba (Cuba) in a family with an extensive musical tradition. Their father, Jorge Vistel, a trumpeter, introduced the brothers to the world of music very early. As teenagers, Jorge and Maikel became highly skilled at jazz improvisation and were soon recognized for their maturity and musicality. Separately each is outstanding, but together, the brothers' connection creates improvisational magic, beautiful ‘conversations’ between trumpet and saxophone. Jorge (trumpeter) and Maikel Vistel (saxophonist) has spent 20 years of artistic career in and out of the Cuba, giving the public sympathy and a strong positive energy on stage. Their music is based on trends of modern jazz and Afro-Cuban music. Vistel Brothers are emotional and passionate artists whose captivating live performances offer the audience a wonderful experience.

A finalist in the 2023 American Pianists Awards, Cardello began his musical journey at age 5, training in both classical and jazz piano. He has been mentored by renowned musicians such as Bill Charlap, Dave Kikoski, and Harold Mabern, which has significantly influenced his artistic development. Cardello leads the Caelan Cardello Trio, performing original compositions and jazz standards at prestigious venues like Mezzrow Jazz Club in New York City and The Kosciuszko Foundation. The trio, which includes Jonathon Muir-Cotton on bass and Domo Branch on drums, has gained recognition for their dynamic performances and innovative arrangements. Cardello has also collaborated with vocal sensation Tyreek McDole, showcasing his ability to work with diverse musical talents. His performances are characterized by a blend of traditional jazz elements and contemporary interpretations, earning him a reputation as a prodigy-turned-powerhouse in the jazz world.

youtube_search_results.title: Cargo Lift Sessions: Pasquale Grasso Trio | Esplanade Offstage
youtube_search_results.description:
“Is it me or is the lift shaking?” said a bemused bassist Ari Roland as the trio ended the first song, a comment which triggered some laughter from everyone present. His partners-in-charm, lead guitarist Pasquale Grasso and drummer Keith Balla, were unfazed in this unusual performance space, just 12 hours after their sold-out show at Jazz in July 2024. With nary a blink, this well-oiled jazz trio quickly and effortlessly got the lift rocking (metaphorically) with two toe-tapping bebop tunes. 

Audio: Andrew Lim 
Video: Made by Identity 

www.esplanade.com/offstage

We believe in making the arts accessible for everyone. As a not-for-profit arts centre, we are driven by our mission to entertain, engage, educate and inspire through the arts. About 70% of our programmes are free!

biography: Pasquale Grasso is a virtuoso jazz guitarist known for his unique blend of jazz and classical guitar styles. Hailed by renowned musician Pat Metheny, Grasso has made a significant impact on the contemporary jazz scene. He leads the Pasquale Grasso Trio, which regularly performs at prestigious venues such as Birdland Jazz Club, Smalls Jazz Club, and Mezzrow in New York City. Grasso's musical accomplishments include the release of a bold trio album titled "Fervency," which showcases his innovative approach to lesser-known tunes and jazz classics. His performances extend beyond New York, with appearances at SF Jazz and other notable venues. Grasso's trio, featuring Ari Roland on bass and Keith Balla on drums, is known for their intimate and dynamic live performances, often interpreting jazz standards with a fresh perspective.

biography: Conrad Herwig is a renowned trombonist, composer, and bandleader who leads the Latin Side All-Stars. Known for his innovative approach to Latin jazz, Herwig has been blending mainstream jazz with Afro-Cuban rhythms for nearly three decades. His "Latin Side" series, which began in 1996, has earned him four Grammy nominations and has reimagined the works of jazz masters through a Latin lens. Herwig's ensemble, the Latin Side All-Stars, features a rotating cast of top-tier musicians, including Bill O'Connell on keys, Robbie Ameen on drums, Lincoln Goines on bass, and Ivan Renta on saxophone. The group has maintained a strong presence in New York City's jazz scene, with regular performances at venues like Django in the Roxy Hotel. Herwig's musical prowess and dedication to exploring the intersection of jazz and Latin music have solidified his position as a significant figure in the contemporary jazz landscape.

youtube_search_results.title: Jazz Party - Delfeayo Marsalis and the Uptown Jazz Orchestra
youtube_search_results.description: Here in New Orleans we never miss a chance to party! We are currently having a virtual blowout in celebration of JazzTimes Magazine naming "Jazz Party," the latest album by Delfeayo Marsalis and the Uptown Jazz Orchestra, #37 on their list of the Top 40 New Jazz Releases of 2020. We are jazzed that critics loved the album, and you can check out a taste here!
youtube_search_results.channel_description:
Uptown Jazz Orchestra was formed in 2009 by NEA Jazz Master Delfeayo Marsalis to keep alive great musical traditions from New Orleans and in American music.  UJO consists of New Orleans' finest musicians whose only objectives are to have a good time and play music that makes you want to shake that thing!

Jeff Simon of the Buffalo News observed, " Delfeayo is, in many ways, the most fun of the Marsalises. He's the family trombonist. And record producer. And he seems to be the family wise guy too!" The Uptown Jazz Orchestra is stretching the boundaries of what is expected from big bands, playing with an extraordinary sense of joy and fun that could only be from New Orleans. With influences from Louis Armstrong to Count Basie and James Brown to J Cole, Marsalis and UJO play music to free the mind, heal the soul, and warm the heart! 

Come join the party, New Orleans style!

biography: Delfeayo Marsalis is a renowned trombonist, NEA Jazz Master, and Grammy Award-winning musician who formed the Uptown Jazz Orchestra (UJO) in 2007. As the leader of this ensemble, Marsalis aims to preserve important jazz traditions, including riff-playing, spontaneous group improvisations, and collective New Orleans instrumental polyphony. His musical accomplishments are extensive, having produced over 120 recordings and earning multiple Grammy nominations in addition to his win. The Uptown Jazz Orchestra, under Marsalis's direction, has become a significant force in contemporary jazz, performing at prestigious venues and festivals across the United States. Their performances are known for keeping alive the vibrant spirit of New Orleans jazz while incorporating modern elements, showcasing Marsalis's commitment to both tradition and innovation in the genre.

With a confidence reflecting an instrumental and compositional maturity that both belie his age and announce the arrival of a remarkable talent, Bryan Carter exudes what promises a highly successful career. Joined by the prodigious talents of Mathis Picard (piano) and Dan Chmielinski (bass), these gentleman promise an unforgettable evening of versatility, sophistication and soul.

Carter studied at The Juilliard School in New York City and has played and/or recorded with notable artists including Clark Terry, McCoy Tyner, Wynton Marsalis, Marcus Roberts, Kenny Barron, Michael Feinstein and Kurt Elling.
youtube_search_results.channel_description:
Monks began as a pop-up listening room in 2016, and has evolved into a state-of-the-art audio and video recording studio and jazz venue in the heart of East Austin. Our curated concert series features the best improvisational jazz groups and musicians the region has to offer. 

When the pandemic hit in early 2020, we pivoted, streaming shows live from a single camera in our founder Collin’s living room. Before long, Collin found a space and relocated to a literal brick and mortar in the Spring of 2021.

Monks was voted “Best Virtual Listening Room” by Austin Chronicle readers in 2021, and our in-studio experience is singular. The venue offers an intimate but casual alternative to loud bars and high-cost performance halls. We aim to foster an environment where all people can enjoy the rich culture of jazz.

Spaulding's repertoire includes tributes to jazz vocalists like Diana Washington, Nancy Wilson, and Nat King Cole, as well as performances honoring old Hollywood starlets of the 1950s and 60s. She has showcased her talents in various venues, including her one-woman show "Hollywood Under the Vine" at Ghost Baby and performances at the Club Room and Reverie Room in New York City. Spaulding often performs with her quartet, demonstrating her versatility as both a solo artist and ensemble leader in the jazz scene.

youtube_search_results.title: Gili Yalo - Coffee | Live Plus Près De Toi
youtube_search_results.description:
Pour bien comprendre la musique, le message, de Gili Yalo, il faut remonter dans le temps, une trentaine d’années en arrière. Nous sommes en plein hiver 1984, l’Éthiopie essuie l’une des plus grandes famines de l’histoire après des années de guerre civile : 1 million de morts et des centaines de milliers d’Éthiopiens qui fuient pour se réfugier dans les pays voisins.

Cet exode, Gili Yalo l’a vécu, chantant sur les épaules de son papa, traversant le désert à pieds nu pour rejoindre les camps de réfugiés soudanais. Survivre d’abord dans ces camps avant d’être sauvé par la légendaire Opération Moïse organisée par l’armée israélienne pour sauver les Juifs éthiopiens et leur offrir une nouvelle vie en Israël. C’est ainsi que Gili Yalo débarque à l’âge de 5 ans du coté de Sfat. Toute une jeunesse à essayer de s’intégrer au mieux, d’adopter totalement et fièrement sa nouvelle vie, son nouveau pays, une nouvelle langue, en mettant de coté son passé érythréen, mais par contre sans jamais s’arrêter de chanter.

Et puis, le déclic, un coup du hasard, mais surtout une prise de conscience, une révolte face à un pays qui, comme trop d’autres aujourd’hui, n’intègre pas comme il le mérite ses populations d’immigrants, travailleuses et discrètes, peut-être un peu trop discrètes… Alors Gili Yalo a replongé dans ses racines, réapprit l’amharique, sa langue originelle, et grâce aux veilles cassettes de sa maman redécouvertes, cette si puissante éthiopique musique, Gili Yalo vient aujourd’hui réveiller les esprits, en portant fièrement la voix de ceux que l’on nomme maladroitement « les Falashas », avec une musique qui a pour ambition de réunir l’orient, l’Afrique et l’occident soit un savant mélange très moderne d’éthio psyché jazz baignant dans le funk et la soul musique.

Son premier album vient tout juste de sortir sur le label Dead Se Records.

Images : Nicolas Lartigue
Son : Emmanuel Baux

*****

biography: Gili Yalo is an Ethiopian-born Israeli singer and musician who has emerged as one of the most intriguing artists in Israel's music scene. His unique sound fuses Ethiopian musical legacy with contemporary genres such as soul, funk, groove, and jazz, incorporating traditional African melodies into modern productions. Yalo's musical journey began during his family's migration from Ethiopia to Israel in 1984, and he has since developed a rich, exceptional style that draws on his heritage and Tel Aviv upbringing. He has collaborated with top music producers like Beno Hendler and Uri Kinrot, releasing albums including his self-titled debut in 2017 and "Made in Amherica" in 2019. Yalo's performances, known for their vibrant tapestry of vintage soul and Ethiopian funk, have garnered attention internationally, with upcoming shows scheduled through 2025.

biography: Diego Campo is a versatile jazz guitarist, artist, music producer, and educator based in New York City. Originally from Switzerland with Spanish roots, Campo has established himself as a prominent figure in the New York jazz scene. He leads multiple ensembles, including the Diego Campo Gypsy Jazz String Quartet and the Diego Campo Trio, which perform regularly at venues across the city. Campo's musical style is deeply rooted in gypsy jazz, swing, and 1920s-30s cinematic sounds, making him a sought-after performer for weddings, private events, and corporate gatherings. His bands can be found playing weekly at St. Mazie in Brooklyn and Flowercat in Greenpoint, as well as at upscale locations like the Campbell, Soho Grand, and Radegast. Campo's dedication to his craft and his ability to create memorable musical experiences have solidified his reputation as one of New York's finest jazz musicians.

biography: David Ostwald's Louis Armstrong Eternity Band is a jazz ensemble dedicated to preserving and celebrating the music of early jazz pioneers. Led by David Ostwald, the group draws inspiration from legendary musicians such as Louis Armstrong, Bix Beiderbecke, Duke Ellington, and Jelly Roll Morton. The band is known for breathing new life and passion into classic jazz compositions, performing regularly at venues like Birdland Jazz Club in New York City. With a focus on traditional jazz styles, the Louis Armstrong Eternity Band has established itself as a notable presence in the contemporary jazz scene, attracting audiences with their authentic interpretations of timeless jazz standards. The group maintains an active touring schedule, performing concerts across North America and keeping the spirit of early jazz alive for modern audiences.

biography: The Smalls Afternoon Jam Session is a recurring event at Smalls Jazz Club in New York City, featuring various hosts and musicians. While there is no single lead musician for the group, notable hosts have included Mimi Jones, Shai Jaschek, Ben Barnett, and Matt Snow. Mimi Jones, a bassist and bandleader, has performed with jazz legends like Yusef Latif and Max Roach, and has showcased her skills in Latin bass techniques. Matt Snow, another prominent host, is a dynamic jazz bassist who has performed at prestigious venues worldwide, including the Blue Note in Tokyo and New York, Jazz Standard, and Dizzy's Club Coca Cola. The jam sessions provide a platform for both established and rising jazz artists to showcase their talents, contributing to the vibrant New York jazz scene.

youtube_search_results.description:
"...one of the greatest living jazz pianists." - Los Angeles Times, July 2011

As always, please subscribe to Alan's newsletter at http://www.alanbroadbent.com

Full version of "If You Could See Me Now" available here:

2-time Grammy Award winning jazz pianist Alan Broadbent performed live at The Kitano in New York City, USA on September 23 and 24, 2011.
Sidemen: Putter Smith on bass and Michael Stephans on drums

This video is a compilation of the first set on Friday, September 23, 2011.

"Solar" from his in 2010 released CD "Live at Giannelli Square, Vol. 1" had been nominated in company with Keith Jarrett, Herbie Hancock, Wynton Marsalis and Hank Jones for „Best Improvised Jazz Solo" 

You can read a review of the 1st set on Saturday, September 24, 2011 by Dan Bilawsky, allaboutjazz.com here: http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/article.php?id=40528

Setlist from the 1st set on Friday, September 23, 2011 (this video):
"Body and Soul" by Johnny Green
"Lullaby of the Leaves" by Bernice Petkere
"Hot House" by Tadd Dameron
"If You Could See Me Now" by Tadd Dameron
"Ceora" by Lee Morgan
"Groovin' High" by Dizzy Gillespie

Alan Broadbent - piano / http://www.alanbroadbent.com
Putter Smith - bass 
Michael Stephans - drums / http://www.michaelstephans.com

The Kitano / http://www.kitano.com

youtube_search_results.description:
This is the first concert in Europe under Alan's own name. Thank you, Walter and friends in Lustenau!

The trio met for the very first time 1h before the concert with a 10min soundcheck.
Alan was on full jetlag having arrived on the same day.
Thank you Phil & Kai.

As always, please subscribe to Alan's newsletter at http://www.alanbroadbent.com

Unfortunately we ran out of battery at the end of the first set, so only a short snippet of Strange Meadowlark.

biography: Alan Broadbent is a renowned New Zealand jazz pianist, arranger, and composer known for his expressive improvisation and mastery of jazz harmony. He has collaborated with numerous notable artists including Charlie Haden, Woody Herman, Chet Baker, and Natalie Cole. Broadbent's musical journey began when he received a Downbeat Magazine scholarship to attend Berklee College of Music in Boston at age 19. He has led his own trio, releasing acclaimed albums such as "Personal Standards" and "You and the Night and the Music," which earned him Grammy nominations for Best Improvised Solo. Broadbent's performances with his trio have been celebrated for their musical sophistication, as evidenced by live recordings like "Live at Giannelli Square, Vol. 1." In recent years, he has also gained recognition for his songwriting collaborations with vocalist-lyricist Georgia Mancio, producing highly regarded albums that showcase their combined talents in jazz composition and lyricism.

youtube_search_results.description:
order:
https://jiheeheo.bandcamp.com/album/flow
https://originarts.com/oa2/recordings...

Now almost 15 years into her New York City life, South Korean pianist and composer Jihee Heo has thrived during her deep journey into the city's towering jazz piano legacy. Her studies in Amsterdam and at the Manhattan School of Music blended experimental jazz with classical and bop, but the rich connection she discovered with drummer Joe Farnsworth and bassist Alex Claffy several years ago awakened sounds she's had stored away since she first encountered jazz. Now a steady presence in New York's clubs, this trio's journey is documented on Flow, which was, appropriately enough, recorded by Maureen Sickler at Rudy Van Gelder's famed studio in Englewood, NJ. Joining the trio for two tunes is the alto titan, Vincent Herring.



"Pianist Jihee Heo has a beautiful legato touch that builds on sturdy lyricism and lustrous harmonies but her work also is filled with delicate, detailed figures."DownBea
