youtube_search_results.channel_description:
The Jazz Exchange is a minority-led organization that curates creative programming, offering audiences
to discover new venues, meet new people, experience new artists, and mentor future generations of young artists.

Born out of a collaboration of mutual admiration, vision and respect for the arts and education the duo Candice Reyes and Abel Mireles lead The Jazz Exchange. The couple not only has a shared musical experiences as professional musicians but shares the vision and belief of the importance of building communities through music and being a part of something larger than yourself.

The Jazz Exchange has gained a reputation in the U.S. and Internationally as an organization that has been preeminent
in supporting underserved artists and local businesses in their communities and fostering the importance of mentorship through music education.

youtube_search_results.description:

Thirteen jazz-inflected Brazilian rock songs on “Vox” result from a two year long recording, writing, and production process between Martins and luminary jazz guitarist Kurt Rosenwinkel.

Vox features Martin’s prolific multi instrumental capacities; On this record he plays guitar, piano/synths, bass, drums, percussion, flute and sings in a beautiful seraphic falsetto. He is also the principle composer, arranger, and wrote most of the lyrics on the record. All together, VOX is a deeply personal and complex journey where the listener is invited to join Martins in his wonderful world of sound and story.

“This album is like a book of stories that happened in my life, and what you can hear there is actually my inner voice narrating those stories through the medium of music”​says Pedro Martins whose album“VOX” (The Voice) will be out February 8th, 2019 on Heartcore Records.

The album features Kurt Rosenwinkel, Brad Mehldau, Chris Potter, Kyle Crane, Frederico Heliodoro, Antonio Loureiro and Oscar Azevedo.

Read more about Pedro Martins

youtube_search_results.channel_description:
Composer, pianist, producer Alessandro Sgobbio keeps expanding his personal vocabulary of compositions, improvisations and spiritual explorations throughout music. Performing internationally as a soloist, duo and also with his band Silent Fires, he has been touring across Europe, Scandinavia, UK, China and the USA. He has issued numerous recordings as a leader/co-leader and has been nominated for the best new talents of the year at the Italian TopJazz.

His recents “Forests” (2019), “Transparence” (2021), “Piano Music” (2022) and “Piano Music 2“ (2023) have received multiple awards for the best album on Musica Jazz Magazine, Jazzism, All About Jazz and other press outlets. 

“I find such an extremely powerful experience to sit on piano, close my eyes and start playing a song dedication. Each piece is like an open trip diary, where the composer, the listener and the person or place whose the music is dedicated - they all can meet, meditate, coexist and write together new stories.”

biography: Eduardo Belo is a Brazilian bassist, composer, and bandleader known for his versatility across various musical styles. He leads the group Belo & The Beasts, which performs original compositions deeply rooted in Brazilian grooves and melodies, offering a modern take on classic Brazilian traditions. Belo has collaborated with renowned musicians such as Michel Camilo, Romero Lubambo, Lee Konitz, and Bebel Gilberto. His ensemble, aptly named "The Beasts," features talented musicians on accordion, flute, and drums. The group regularly performs at venues like Lunatico in Brooklyn, showcasing their dynamic blend of Brazilian-influenced jazz. Belo's musical prowess and innovative approach to Brazilian music have established him as a notable figure in the contemporary jazz and world music scenes.

youtube_search_results.description:
[Brandon Lee]
Brandon Lee is a free-lance jazz trumpeter, composer and arranger based in NYC. He has led and recorded 3 projects under his name, and 2 projects as co-leader of Uptown Jazz Tentet. He is a member of the world-famous Count Basie Orchestra, and the Grammy Award Winning Christian McBride Big Band. Brandon studied at The Juilliard School under the tutelage of Wynton Marsalis, Mark Gould, and Joe Wilder. He has also taught at Juilliard (2009-12), as well as the University of North Carolina, Greensboro (2013-18).

#corementor

We are 12Petals: www.weare12petals.com
Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/weare12petals/
Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/weare12Petals/

MISSION:
At 12Petals, our mission is to create a healthier ecosystem that empowers and uplifts others through music.

VISION:
12Petals believes that empowering mentors and mentees who seek to improve the lives of the people around them through music and education is the best way to create more opportunities globally.

VALUES:
We value the growth mindset, diversity, adaptability and our personal stories.

OUR CORE VALUES:
The Growth Mindset
We see failures not as a property of our identities, but as opportunities to exceed our assumed limitations and expand our understanding of what's possible for us. We thrive on challenges, and we stay curious about what we're capable of.

Diversity
12Petals is global and cross-disciplinary. Our mentors are not only from the classical music scene but also folk, jazz, film, production, marketing, management, administrative industries and many more. We cultivate an environment for our mentors and mentees to discover entirely new life pathways.

Adaptability
The world is changing faster than ever. In a harshly competitive global environment, the ability to change and maintain effectiveness and relevance can determine the quality of life. At 12Petals we respect the classics, but we accept that times change and that new ways may need to be embraced. 

Our Personal Stories
Musicianship can be brutal. We've all struggled with the decisions on giving up, persevering, or pivoting. At 12Petals we encourage the refining of our stories. We believe in allowing ourselves to see where we've built physical, mental, emotional, and social resilience through our hardships.

ABOUT US:
12Petals is a community dedicated to accelerating the growth and nourishing the well-being of aspiring and professional young individuals in the music, arts, and education industries. We believe in building meaningful connections and creating more global opportunities by empowering and uplifting others, as well as looking at music, education and life from different lenses.

We do this by connecting professionals with mentees through workshops, panel discussions, direct mentorship, and more. Through these programs, we strive both to bring clearer awareness to the common pitfalls of our craft and to purify our awareness of its true value.

youtube_search_results.title: BIMHUIS TV Presents: Gilad Hekselman Trio - part 1
youtube_search_results.description:
Crystal clear and at the same time warm: meet this top of the bill guitar trio from New York.

Gilad Hekselman guitar, Petros Klampanis double bass, Amir Bressler drums

Gilad Hekselman is one of those guitar players who seduces you with a warm, clean tone, and will move you to the edge of your seat with breathtaking improvisations. He has established himself as one of the leading voices in jazz guitar. While he regularly collaborates with top players in all kinds of bands, it’s his own trio in which he can truly stretch out. Here he plays his own music, which can be described as melodic, narrative and full of surprising twists and turns. Timeless, as you can expect from the classic guitar, bass and drums line-up.

biography: Gilad Hekselman is an accomplished Israeli jazz guitarist known for his innovative approach to the instrument. He leads the Gilad Hekselman Trio, a dynamic ensemble that showcases his compositional skills and improvisational prowess. Hekselman's music blends elements of modern jazz with influences from blues, soul, and Hebrew folk traditions. His latest album, "Downhill From Here," released in January 2025, features original compositions like "Wise Man" and "Scoville," the latter a tribute to guitar legend John Scofield. The album also includes interpretations of standards such as Burt Bacharach's "Alfie" and the Hebrew folk song "Like A Wildflower." Hekselman frequently collaborates with renowned musicians, including drummer Marcus Gilmore, who has been a long-standing creative partner since 2008. The guitarist has also been part of other notable projects, such as Trio Grande with Will Vinson and Antonio Sánchez. Hekselman's performances, including appearances at prestigious venues like Smalls Jazz Club in New York, continue to solidify his reputation as a leading voice in contemporary jazz guitar.
